orangelight.title: Design the biased search results reporting form

comments.body: One thing that's been expressed by the implementation team is the desire to be consistent and use UI patterns for reporting harmful language that we already have in place. The team has pointed to the lower tray of "buttons" on the Finding Aids and the Catalog record/show pages as something users may be familiar with. I wonder if this is the best approach though? I find these buttons to be a bit hard to see. I wonder if we would include the "Ask a Question" and "Suggest a Correction" links, or if we would simply have one gray button for "Report Biased Results"? We can contrast the original mockup that has a "banner/announcement" pattern with the mockup that uses the existing UI "button tray" pattern for interacting with PUL Staff. My question is "Would one large Report Biased Results button at the bottom essentially serve as a less visible and descriptive banner?" Thoughts? New Mockup: Original Mockup:

Adding breadcrumbs:
Following the [troubleshooting steps](https://docs.datadoghq.com/database_monitoring/setup_postgres/troubleshooting/#pg-stat-statements-not-created) for the most recent error showed that `pg_stat_statements` did not exist on `lib-postgres-prod1`:
```
$ psql -h localhost -U datadog -d postgres -c "select * from pg_stat_statements LIMIT 1;"
Password for user datadog: 
ERROR:  relation "pg_stat_statements" does not exist
```
I followed the docs to create it:
```
postgres=# CREATE EXTENSION pg_stat_statements;
CREATE EXTENSION
```
which brought me to:
```
$ psql -h localhost -U datadog -d postgres -c "select * from pg_stat_statements LIMIT 1;"
Password for user datadog: 
ERROR:  pg_stat_statements must be loaded via shared_preload_libraries
```
The [docs on pg_stat_statements](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/15/pgstatstatements.html) say we need to update `postgresql.conf` - and also that enabling `pg_stat_statements` requires additional shared memory.
